    # This is week 4 Data analysis and visualization (Lists, Pandas & Matplotlib)
    # List of 10 integers
    integers = [5, 12, 23, 34, 7, 18, 65, 43, 21, 10]

    # Range of 100 numbers
    numbers_range = list(range(1, 101))

    # List of 10 fruits
    fruits = ["apple", "banana", "orange", "grape", "kiwi", "mango", "pear", "pineapple", "peach", "cherry"]

    # Mixed list: student name, ID, grades, and pass status
    student_info = ["Alice", 12345, [89, 74, 92], "Pass"]

    # Extend the list of 10 integers by 1 element and then 5 elements
    integers.append(99) # Adding 1 element
    integers.extend([56, 67, 78, 88, 90]) # Adding 5 more elements

    # Delete the last 50 numbers of the range list
    numbers_range = numbers_range[:50] # Keep the first 50 elements

    # Extend the list of fruits by adding 5 more fruits
    more_fruits = ["papaya", "plum", "watermelon", "strawberry", "blueberry"]
    fruits.extend(more_fruits)

    # Extend the integers list by adding the fruits list
    integers.extend(fruits)

    # Print all modified lists
    print("Updated list of integers:", integers)
    print("Updated range of numbers:", numbers_range)
    print("Updated list of fruits:", fruits)
    print("Mixed student info:", student_info)

    # S&P 500 and FTSE 100 data points

    sp500_values = [4740.49, 4757.01, 4766.28, 4780.51, 4791.92]

    ftse100_dates = ["05/01", "05/02", "05/03", "05/06", "05/07"]
    ftse100_values = [7725.93, 7753.08, 7758.35, 7781.70, 7791.87]

    # Plot separate graphs for S&P 500 and FTSE 100
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(10, 8), sharex=True)

    # S&P 500 Plot
    axs[0].plot(sp500_dates, sp500_values, marker='o', color='blue', label='S&P 500')
    axs[0].set_title("S&P 500 Index")
    axs[0].set_ylabel("Index Value")
    axs[0].legend()

    # FTSE 100 Plot
    axs[1].plot(ftse100_dates, ftse100_values, marker='o', color='green', label='FTSE 100')
    axs[1].set_title("FTSE 100 Index")
    axs[1].set_xlabel("Date")
    axs[1].set_ylabel("Index Value")
    axs[1].legend()

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    import numpy as np

    # Generating synthetic data for scatter and bar charts
    np.random.seed(42)
    days = np.arange(1, 41)
    values1 = np.random.uniform(100, 500, 40) # Random values for dataset 1
    values2 = np.random.uniform(200, 600, 40) # Random values for dataset 2

    # Plotting scatter and bar charts
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(12, 10))

    # Scatter plot
    ax[0].scatter(days, values1, color='purple', label='Dataset 1')
    ax[0].scatter(days, values2, color='orange', label='Dataset 2')
    ax[0].set_title('Scatter Plot of Two Datasets')
    ax[0].set_xlabel('Days')
    ax[0].set_ylabel('Values')
    ax[0].legend()

    # Bar chart
    width = 0.35 # Bar width
    ax[1].bar(days - width/2, values1, width, color='purple', label='Dataset 1')
    ax[1].bar(days + width/2, values2, width, color='orange', label='Dataset 2')
    ax[1].set_title('Bar Chart of Two Datasets')
    ax[1].set_xlabel('Days')
    ax[1].set_ylabel('Values')
    ax[1].legend()

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
